<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Group Reset Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Resets all Event Points in the same colour and letter group to their alive and unactivated state.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Group Reset Event Points Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A <Bold>Group Reset</Bold> Event Point resets every Event Point that shares its
        <Bold>colour</Bold> and <Bold>letter group</Bold> to an <Bold>alive and unactivated</Bold>
        state. This means the target Event Points become alive (able to process) but also
        unactivated (as if they had not yet fired).
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Group Reset is rare in retail missions - only 4 instances exist, all in driving/testdrive
        missions. It is used when a mission needs to reuse a set of Event Points multiple times, such
        as resetting checkpoints in a driving course or clearing a failed objective so it can be
        retried. Like Group Life and Group Death, it has no type-specific Data settings - the colour
        and group it targets come from the Event Point's standard common properties.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical meaning:</Run>
                <Run> Set this Event Point's Colour and Group to match the set of Event Points you want to reset. When the Group Reset fires, every waypoint with that exact colour+group returns to alive and unactivated.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Group Reset uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point type,
        letter group, colour, position, facing direction, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The index number and Event Point type are automatic. <Bold>Colour</Bold> and
        <Bold>letter group</Bold> are the critical fields - they determine which Event Points this
        Group Reset will affect. Position is usually not what matters for the reset itself, but can
        be used to keep the Group Reset near its target set for organisation.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Colour
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Colour is one half of the targeting selector. A Group Reset with <Bold>White</Bold> affects
        only Event Points that also use <Bold>White</Bold>. All other colours are ignored. The
        colour field is in the common Event Point properties section.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Group (Letter)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Group letter is the other half of the selector. A Group Reset with letter <Bold>A</Bold>
        affects only Event Points that also use letter <Bold>A</Bold>. The combination of
        <Bold>Colour + Group</Bold> is what defines the target set. White/A is different from
        White/B or Green/A.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Position does not affect which Event Points are reset. Group Reset targets by colour+group,
        not by spatial radius. Use position only for placing the Event Point somewhere logical for
        mission authoring, such as near the checkpoint or objective that should be reset.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        All retail Group Reset Event Points use <Bold>Dependency</Bold>. The reset happens when
        another Event Point fires, such as a fail condition, checkpoint restart, or objective retry
        trigger.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Listening Mode
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Most retail Group Reset examples use <Bold>Active</Bold>. One uses <Bold>Active While</Bold>,
        which keeps resetting the group as long as the dependency condition remains true. Use
        <Bold>Active</Bold> for a one-time reset and <Bold>Active While</Bold> only when the group
        should be continuously reset while a condition is active.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Group Reset-Specific Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Group Reset has <Bold>no type-specific Data settings</Bold>. The Event Point's behaviour is
        entirely determined by the Colour and Group fields in the common properties section, plus
        the trigger that causes it to fire.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> Group Reset is useful for missions with retry mechanics, checkpoints, or repeatable objectives. Set the retry/fail Event Point as the Dependency trigger so the group resets when the player needs to try again.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        How Missions Trigger Group Reset
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Existing Group Reset usage is focused entirely on driving missions with checkpoint or retry
        mechanics. The only observed trigger pattern is:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> with <Bold>Active</Bold> - the standard pattern. The group is reset when another Event Point fires, such as a checkpoint trigger, fail condition, or retry action.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> with <Bold>Active While</Bold> - used when the group should be continuously reset as long as the dependency condition remains true. This is less common but observed in one retail mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run> Group Reset affects every Event Point with the matching Colour+Group. Make sure the Colour+Group combination is used only by the Event Points you intend to reset, not by unrelated mission logic.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Group Reset Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Checkpoint Or Retry Reset</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> with <Bold>Active</Bold> when a set of Event Points should be
        reset after a checkpoint trigger, fail condition, or retry action. This is the standard
        Group Reset pattern.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>testdrive1a.ucm</Bold>, Group Reset <Bold>292</Bold> targets <Bold>White/A</Bold>
        and uses <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point <Bold>234</Bold> with listening mode
        <Bold>Active</Bold>. When Event Point <Bold>234</Bold> fires, all White/A Event Points are
        reset to alive and unactivated.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Set the Event Points that should be reset to a specific Colour+Group, for example
        <Bold>White/A</Bold>. Add a <Bold>Group Reset</Bold> Event Point with the same
        <Bold>White/A</Bold> combination, set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>Dependency</Bold>,
        and set <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the Event Point that represents the checkpoint or retry
        trigger. Use listening mode <Bold>Active</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Continuous Reset With Active While</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Active While</Bold> instead of <Bold>Active</Bold> when the group should be
        continuously reset as long as the dependency condition remains true. This is uncommon but
        useful for specific driving or checkpoint scenarios.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>testdrive2.ucm</Bold>, Group Reset <Bold>140</Bold> targets <Bold>Green/A</Bold>
        and uses <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point <Bold>139</Bold> with listening mode
        <Bold>Active While</Bold>. As long as Event Point <Bold>139</Bold> remains active, the
        Green/A group is continuously reset.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use <Bold>Active While</Bold> instead of <Bold>Active</Bold> when the dependency Event Point
        represents a persistent condition rather than a one-time trigger. Test carefully, because
        continuous resetting can cause unintended loops if the group's own behaviour re-triggers the
        dependency.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Driving Mission Checkpoint System</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Group Reset is most commonly found in driving missions where checkpoints or stages need to
        be reset if the player fails or retries.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Three of the four retail Group Reset instances are in <Bold>testdrive</Bold> missions
        (<Bold>testdrive1a.ucm</Bold>, <Bold>testdrive2.ucm</Bold>, and <Bold>testdrive3.ucm</Bold>).
        Each uses <Bold>White/A</Bold> or <Bold>Green/A</Bold> as the target Colour+Group and resets
        the group when a checkpoint or retry Event Point fires.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        For a driving or checkpoint mission, assign all checkpoint-related Event Points to a common
        Colour+Group. Add a Group Reset that triggers on the fail condition or retry action. This
        lets the player restart the checkpoint sequence without leaving the mission.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Rare Usage Outside Driving Missions</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Group Reset is almost never used outside of driving/checkpoint missions. If a mission does
        not have retry or repeatable objective mechanics, Group Life and Group Death are usually
        sufficient for controlling group activation.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed pattern</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Of 16,259 Event Points across 76 retail missions, only <Bold>4</Bold> are Group Reset. All
        4 are in driving/testdrive missions. No combat, objective, or exploration missions use Group
        Reset in retail data.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to apply</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Only use Group Reset when a mission genuinely needs to reset a group of Event Points to
        their unactivated state. For most missions, Group Life (activate) and Group Death
        (deactivate) are sufficient. Group Reset is specifically for retry and checkpoint mechanics.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Group Reset Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Confirm the mission needs reset mechanics. If it does not have checkpoints, retries, or repeatable objectives, Group Reset is probably not needed.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create or identify the Event Points that should be reset together as a group.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set all of those Event Points to the same <Bold>Colour</Bold> and <Bold>Group</Bold> letter combination.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Group Reset</Bold> Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the Group Reset's <Bold>Colour</Bold> and <Bold>Group</Bold> to match the target set.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>Dependency</Bold> and <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the Event Point that should trigger the reset, such as a checkpoint trigger or fail condition.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use listening mode <Bold>Active</Bold> for a one-time reset or <Bold>Active While</Bold> for continuous reset.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test the reset carefully and confirm the group returns to alive and unactivated as expected.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Verify that no unintended Event Points share the same Colour+Group, which would cause them to reset along with the intended group.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test that the reset does not create an unintended loop where the group's behaviour re-triggers the reset dependency.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final checklist:</Run>
                <Run> The mission genuinely needs reset mechanics, the Group Reset's Colour+Group matches the target Event Points exactly, the dependency fires only when the reset should happen, and no reset loops are created.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
